Simple Linear Regression Intuition, 
Linearity means there is a relationship between two or more variables, taking a 2-dimensional 
space, linear relationship between two variables in that space is represented by a straight line. 
Linear regression predicts an dependent variable based on a dependent variable. Performing a 
simple regression is finding the best fitting line between the two variables and that line is used 
to get predicted output or dependent variable. 

Formula for Linear Regression 
y(output) = b0 + b1x1 
terms in the formula, 
y = output 
b0 = constant 
x1 = independent variable 
b1 = coefficient of the independent variable 

Independent variables affect dependent variable, sometimes they dont but there is an 
association between them. 
b1 is how a unit change in independent variable affects a unit change in output. 

y(output) = b0 + b1x1 
y(output) = dependent variable 
b1x1 = independent variable 

Independent variables affect dependent variables 
Sometimes independent variables dont affect dependent variables but there is an 
association between the two. 

b1 => coefficient of the independent variable, how a unit change in x1 affects a unit change in 
y(output)
b0 => constant, is the value at which the fitted line in the dataset crosses the y-axis. 


This is the easiest to describe, use salary and experience.
Salary => Vertical axis, Experience => Horizontal axis. 
Putting a line through the dataset or chart, the line is the best line that fits the data. 
best fitting line is tells us what salary should be payed based on the model. 

Getting the best fitting line, using ordinary least squares 
y1 = actual output 
yhat = predicted output 
to get the best fitting line out of lots of lines drawn in the chart and counts the sum of squares using 
ordinary least squares and finds the minimum, which is the best fitting line. 
SUM(y1 - yhat) pow 2, square the distance between y1 and yhat and find the minimum. 